Intuition
The goal is to remove all occurrences of a given value val from the array in-place and return the count of remaining elements.
Since the order of elements does not matter and no extra space is allowed, a two-pointer approach is a natural fit. We can overwrite unwanted elements while scanning the array.

Approach
I maintain two pointers:

left: iterates through every element in the array.

right: tracks the position where the next valid (non-val) element should be placed.

Steps:

Handle small edge cases such as empty arrays or arrays of size 1 where the single element equals val.

Traverse the array using left.

Whenever nums[left] is not equal to val, copy it to nums[right] and increment right.

After traversal, right represents the count of elements not equal to val.

The first right elements of nums will contain the desired result.

Complexity
Time complexity:
O(n)

Space complexity:
O(1)

Code
class Solution {
    public int removeElement(int[] nums, int val) {
        
        if(nums.length<=2){
           if(nums.length==0){
            return 0;
           }
           else if ((nums.length==1) && (nums[0]==val))
           {
            return 0;
           }
          
        }
        int left =0;
        int right =0;
        for(left=0; left<nums.length;left++){
            if(nums[left] !=val){
            nums[right]= nums[left];
            right +=1;
            }
        }
        return right;
    }
}
